ver the way in which it is achieved must recognise and address the unique feat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ures of the UK market. A bespoke approach that plays to consumer preferences, our national infrastructure assets and the strengths of the existing heating sector is required. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are investing in the technologies that could enable such a transformation incl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uding, Heat Recovery, Micro-Combined Heat and Power, Gas Heat Pumps, Solar Heating and Electric Heat Pumps.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is vital to ensure implementation of the Heat Strategy supports the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> manufacturing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sector and drives innovation an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d employment growth in the UK al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ongside decarbonisation and bill reductions.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#c00000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is the government taking the right approach to reduce heat energy demand?</span><br /><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BDR Thermea supports </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the government’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aim </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">decarbonis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK heating. However the way in which it is achieved must recognise and address the unique features of the UK market </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A range of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technologies  could enable a transformation including, Heat Recovery, Micro-Combined Heat and Power, Gas Heat Pumps, Solar Heati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng and Electric Heat Pumps.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Off-gas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">19% of the UK housing stock is not connected to the gas grid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> leaving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4 million homes exposed to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">high cost of electricity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LPG,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">experiencing the highest incidence of fuel poverty – yet lack</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> capital for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">alternatives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Electricity decarbonisation and distribution reinforcement is expensive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government has limited resources to support low-carbon technologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> therefore s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">upport should prioritise the more accessible and sizeable carbon reductions in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al heat market</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Policy should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reflect </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">segmentation within the rural heat market</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. For example, heat pumps are best suited to small to medium heat loads and biomass is better suited to larger heat loads. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The 4th Carbon Budget sets a target of 100,000 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">domestic biomass boiler installations by 2020: rising to 1 million by 2030</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> however, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">neither the RESOM nor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ESME modelling scenarios</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> included as an annex to the heat </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> show high deployment of biomass in 2050.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Biomass has a unique role to play in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> decarbonisation of off-grid heat. Biomass </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">meets </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">customer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> expectations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regarding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">warmth, running costs, retrofit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> installation etc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proven technology using wood pellet fuel that is cheaper and less price volatile than heating oil, LPG, coal and elec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tricity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">secure emissions reductions regardless of the pace of grid decarbonisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ready to roll out now</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Biomass is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">often the best or only practicable renewable solution for the decarbonisation of large off-grid properties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BDR Thermea </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strongly believes that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support for renewable heating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> targeted where it will be most effective and to households across all levels of income</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Heat Strategy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more accurately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reflect </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the needs of the off-gird market</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The on-gas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">market</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">80% of residential heating emissions are from on-gas housing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. A l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ow cost, efficient supply chain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> exist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">deliver</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">high confidence and comfort</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government has recognised the continued importance of gas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Future of Heating, Meeting the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Challenge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sees the continuation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of some natural gas for heating out to 2050.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Decarbonisation of the electricity grid is very expensive and will take a considerable time. Gas is an efficient and flexible product and until decarbonisation of the elec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tricity system is achieved efficient gas heating products will be necessary to achieve reductions in emissions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DECC’s updated strategic framework for low carbon heat in buildings over time shows that gas heating of suburban properties dominates into the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2030s. Gas transition technologies includ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> micro combined heat and power</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (mCHP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, hybrids and g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as heat pumps (GHPs)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are suited to this market.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">MCHP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">units which can produce both heat and electricity very efficiently, such as the Baxi Ecogen, can play an important role. The Baxi Ecogen combines a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ondensing gas boiler with power generation. It is capable of supporting the electrical system through deman</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">esponse and low carbon generation, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in addition to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">meeting home heating requirements.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Hybrids </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">present are a suitable retrofit for a large number of homes. BDR Thermea is bringing a hybrid heating solution to market which combines an electric air source h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eat pump for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">base load heating (50-60%) with a condensing gas boiler for peak heat demand. It is less expensive and lower impact on electrical system than an electric heat pump alone.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Gas heat pumps</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (GHP) combine the advantages of two common heating tech</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nologies, gas boilers and heat pumps, to generate renewable heat. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GHPs draw energy from the air using heat pump technology and generate heat by utilising gas locally at very high efficiencies of up to 150%. High efficiencies generate significant carbon and</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on-going costs savings. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GHPs can readily address the needs of the retrofit environment and achieve rapid efficiency and decarbonisation gains without infrastructure changes or loss of comfort. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A number of companies develop a wide range of highly efficien</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t GHP products in the UK with diverse sizes and technical characteristics that can accommodate diverse properties. The technology is commercialised both in the ‘on’ and ‘off’ gas grid sectors. Aside from carbon reduction potential and significant compatibi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lity with the UK market, GHPs are a heating technology that can readily contribute to the attainment of binding renewable targets. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GHPs are an established technology in Europe but RHI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on par with other renewable heating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is essential to provide the necessary incentive, exposure and certainty to start the GHP market in the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RHI support would allow G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">HPs to achieve the strategic potential foreseen in DECC’s Heat Strategy and enable prompt decarbonisation and renewable gai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ns even i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> gas utilisation persists.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#c00000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What progress is the government making on reducing the demand for heat?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BDR Thermea supports and welcomes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">policies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> aimed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at reducing the demand for heat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">however policy measures must </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recognise and address </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the unique features of the UK market</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and its housing stock.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK has some of the least thermally efficiency housing in Europe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">illions of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">homes and businesses are using older inefficient heating systems which rarely break down and can be easily repaired by engineers. In a capital constrained economy, consumers have neither the immediate need </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or finance necessary to replace their heating sys</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">em. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Common features of these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">hard to treat heat’’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> properties </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> include:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Older heating systems which are easy to maintain and repair</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Financial constraints </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Physical constraints (age of central heating, flue location etc)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Low awareness of alternatives</span></li></ul></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Most “hard to treat homes” will not meet the energy efficiency criteria to qualify for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RHI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scheme and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Building regulations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only capture those properties undergoing renovation. An additional barrier is that consumers are reluctant to pay for advice such</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Green Deal assessments as energy efficiency is pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rceived as allow priority expenditure.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Most owners do not qualify for assistance under </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ECO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A practical approach is therefore to target low carbon and renewable heating solutions at those buildings </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which are using the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> most harmful fuels such as off-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gas grid properties and are hardest to reduce demand i.e. “hard to treat”. Carbon savings and value for money will be much higher when a renewable system is installed in these circumstances compared to a b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uilding where demand can be substantially reduced through efficiency and where the primary heating fuel is gas.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A very </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">positive step </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would be Government setting out a pathway for regulatory change.  A long-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">term signal, setting out an intention to tighten r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etro-fit standards for heating systems would give business the confidence to invest.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s backing away from the Zero carbon homes commitment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">requiring the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lesser </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">FEES+ standard’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> instead of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> more ambitious Halfway standard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unhelpful development in the journey to reduce demand for heat. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#c00000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Biomass is deemed a key fuel for heat production from both the cost and GHG perspectives. What should be done to ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represent an accurate pict</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ure?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">According to DECC’s Heat Strategy, sustainable biomass which delivers lifecycle greenhouse gas emissions savings and is not sourced from land with high carbon stock or high biodiversity value will have a key role to play towards decarbonising heat in the U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">K. BDR Thermea backs this objective; the company has participated in a consortium of biomass heating developers that supported the implementation of ambitious sustainability and air quality standards under the RHI to reward good practice and instil market </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">confidence</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DECC, established under the RHI scheme stringent fuel sustainability requirements as prerequisites to receive RHI support. Therefore consumers that do not source fuel from a supplier registered on an approved supplier list of companies that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">meet GHG lifecycle emissions criteria will not be able to receive support. We believe that this is a positive measure that will place those suppliers that do not comply with sustainability criteria at major competitive disadvantage. BDR Thermea would suppo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rt more ambitious criteria as market and policy develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#c00000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">There are sustainability guidelines for biomass, do these go far enough?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BDR Thermea supports the introduction of sustainability regulations for Biomass but believes there should be a distinction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> between the use of biomass to generate electricity, fuel and heat. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Generating electricity by burning pure biomass is approximately 30-35% efficient but burning the same material to produce heat is 85% </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">efficient. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Heating is the most efficient use of biomas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s and this use should not be penalised by stricter regulation that may be required in other sectors. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#c00000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What will the local environmental impact (for example air pollution) be from the use heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local environmental pollution is an important issue for the low carbon heating sector. It is currently a rather confusing area and one with the potential for misinformation and speculation.  A recent report commissioned by a London Borough made derogatory </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">claims about the environmental pollution of CHP which were unjustified and potentially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">damaging for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the industry. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Another area of confusion is the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">application of air quality rules in planning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. There </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> number of different standards and requirements to manage air pollution including the Clean Air Act and Air Quality Regulations which lead </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> having to navigate a range of different standards and requirements across the country. Such regulations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">need to have a consistent approach to facilitate understanding and compliance.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Air quality and appliance efficiency standards should reward good practice and instil market confidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> national</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> approach would be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">helpful. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In either CHP or gas boiler</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> insta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">llations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, if NOx emissions are less than 70mg/kWh the appliance is classed as level 5, an ultra-low emissions class. There is currently no higher level. Therefore provided this level is met, the installation of CHP units should have minimal effect on air p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ollution </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">when </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">replacing a condensing boiler but provide a more energy efficient way of providing heat and power.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#c00000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pumps?</span><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Heat pumps are able to deliver very efficient electrical heating. They use an evaporation and compression cycle to transfer outdoor heat from the air or the ground into buildings. This increased efficiency is important in limiting bills and in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reducing the burden heating at peak </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">times place</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the electricity grid. However, the carbon savings that electric heat pumps are able to deliver depend on the d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecarbonisation of the electricity grid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This is proving to be both a lengthy and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">expensive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cess. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gas is an efficient and flexible fuel and until decarbonisation of the electricity system is achieved efficient gas heating products will be necessary to achieve reductions in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">carbon </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emissions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The relative prices of gas and electricity also favour </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gas at a time when consumers are struggling to pay high energy bills. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are a number of very efficient products which can be utilised to maximise the advantages of gas whilst minimising ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rbon emissions:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Micro combined heat and power (mCHP)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> units </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oduce both h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eat and electricity.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The electricity is generated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the home </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thus avoiding the transmission losses that resul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t from centralised generation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">See paragraph 10 f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r further </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Hybrids</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> present are a suitable retrofit for a large number of homes</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – see paragraph 11.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Gas heat pumps</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (GHP) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can readily address the needs of the retrofit environment and achieve rapid efficiency and decarbonisation gains without infrastructure changes or loss </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of comfort</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> see paragraph 12 and 13 for more information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GHPs are a heating technology that can readily contribute to the attainment of binding renewable targets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> RHI support on par with other renewable heating technologies, is essential to provide the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">necessary incentive, exposure and certainty to start the GHP market in the UK. RHI support would allow GHPs to achieve the strategic potential foreseen in DECC’s Heat Strategy and enable prompt decarbonisation and renewable gains even in case gas utilisati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on persists.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#c00000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Initial results from the DECC heat networks model suggested 20% of UK domestic heat might be met by community heating schemes by 2030. These networks offered higher efficiency gains than individual heating systems. The DECC RESOM model further suggested th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at older buildings and urban areas particularly benefited from district heating, with even non-domestic buildings integrated in a heat network saving up to 7% on the current UK heat demand. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government has introduced schemes and funding to encourage community heating but the most significant barrier to uptake of these schemes in the UK is a lack of information and experience of district heating networks. More community heating pilot scheme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s and publicity and promotion of them would help to remove this barrier. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An example of a community heat scheme that Baxi is involved in is the refurbishment of 14 two-storey maisonettes.  The incentive for the scheme was a requirement from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">funders which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">equired the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Housing Association to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its refurbished properties </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reduced c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arbon </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ioxide emissions in line with 2050 targets.  Due to the high requirement for the houses’ base heating load, two Baxi Ecogens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> were specified, with a standard boiler back-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">up, to deliver heating and hot water for up to ten years.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Community energy could benefit from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> common technical standards, procurement processes, financing arrangements, installation approaches and consumer awareness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Baxi are committed to working to im</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prove the level of community energy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">schemes and would be happy to work </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Departments to progress this opportunity.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#c00000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the lock-in, costs and GHG savings from the promotion of different forms of domestic heating solution? </span><br /><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">echnol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ogies installed under the RHI such as biomass boilers, ASHP, GSHP and Solar Thermal the lock in is up to 20 years. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For gas boilers lock-in costs are around ten years, and oil boilers are around 15 years. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Therefore, consumers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> installing these types of techn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ology now</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will still be using</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> them, and generating emissions,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> well into the 2020s. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Had they installed a renewable technology, the emissions savings per annum when compared to an A-rated oil boiler and for mCHP compared to a gas boiler are given in the bel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ow table.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:12.6pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; bor