>system improvements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and awareness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> raising</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The domestic RHI scheme is a first positive st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ep towards encouraging consumers to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ake up </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">electric </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heat pumps</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n increase in the Value for Money cap would be helpful as Ground Source Heat Pumps (GSHP), are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">constrained</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by this despite being good value for money compared to other means of prod</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ucing renewable energy. The case for increasing the subsidies paid to GSHPs, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is strong. Although </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">initially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">subsidy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uld need to be higher than for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> some other technologies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">deployed to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">meet the renewables target, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t would be worthwhile to ensure p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">deployment of GSHP.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Gas heat pumps</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (GHP) are not included in the RHI despite being an established heating solution that combines the advantages of two common heating technologies, gas boilers and heat pumps, to generate renewable heat. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">See parag</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">phs 12 and 13 for further information. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GHPs are the only key renewable heating solution currently not supported under the RHI.  The European Commission decision on establishing guidelines on calculating renewable energy from heat pumps confirms that GHPs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are a renewable solution, on par with electricity driven heat pumps. Support is essential to provide the necessary incentive, exposure and certainty to start the GHP market in the UK and address existing market distortion in the heat pump sector. RHI suppo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rt would also allow GHPs to achieve the strategic potential foreseen in DECC’s Heat Strategy - one of the two scenarios of DECC’s Heat Strategy foresees that GHPs will be the dominant heating solution in the UK from 2025 onwards - and enable prompt decarbo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nisation and renewable gains even in case gas utilisation persists.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#c00000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Having waited so long for the RHI to be rolled out there may be an initial surge of demand. DECC should recognise it as this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">attempt to introduce </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tariff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> degression measures. Stability is what is now required.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The RHI should include a range of technologies and let the customer, with appropriate advice, select the most effective heating solution for his/her particular pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">perty and circumstances. However, gas heat pumps, an important technology which can make a significant contribution to reducing emissions and consumer bills, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> excluded from the RHI. This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is likely to lead to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">distorti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on of the market.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#c00000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Thermal storage </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">is a potential useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally and annually. What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The uptake of intermittent renewable generation technologies, alo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng with the deployment of solutions that will increase electricity demand - such as electric heat pumps or electric cars - will place significant strain on the electricity grid. The deployment of domestic low carbon heating technologies that generate heat </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and electricity close to the point of consumption can help mitigate strain on the electricity grid, particularly when combined with energy storage solutions. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hermal storage solutions can be integrated with microgeneration technologies providing benefit t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o the grid by balancing peak loads and to consumers by reducing bills. We see considerable interplay with the below domestic heating solutions:</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Micro CHP:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Several novel micro CHP solutions - particularly fuel cells - are designed to follow domestic electri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">city load which does not always coincide with heat demand. Combination with heat storage solutions could allow full use of heat generated on-site allowing maximisation of technology benefits</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Electric heat pumps:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Heat storage could allow electric heat pumps</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to operate during periods of lower electricity demand (e.g. overnight) thus alleviating system strain as a result of heat pump proliferation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To allow the exciting prospects of low carbon heating technologies with thermal storage, policy innovation is nec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">essary to give the right </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">market </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">signals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The implementation of dynamic, or time-of-use, electricity tariffs could provide effectively such signals and drive investment and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">change in consumer behaviour based on the expectation of bill savings. Until the imp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lementation of dynamic electricity tariffs support for thermal storage is necessary. Germany with its recent decision to provide grants and soft loans to consumers to take up storage in combination with microgeneration provides a precedent o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> effective and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> brave policy support.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> See biomass industry charter: </span><a href="http://www.installeronline.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/BiomassCharterFinal2013.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.installeronline.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/BiomassCharterFinal2013.pdf</span></a></p></body></html>